Republican strategy to counter Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat election fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, dismisses the latter as a myth, saying that voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have documented only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in the last ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
With this in mind, most US governments enacted new laws starting in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has intensified after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the time for early voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on election day and deprive citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
For the past two years, they've sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs over a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
It's more than that.
Students, voters who are considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
However, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more Republican to use the cards issued by those clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
But it turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 sponsored legislation abolishing voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states to reduce early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33 percent of early voters were African-American, while the latter represented only 13 percent of voters in the state.
The same was true of Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of early voters.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by vetoes from Democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules introduced will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that were passed and see them as a clear goal to influence the 2012 election results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will undermine the American democratic system in part.
Prostate Cancer Screening - Should You Take the Test or Not?
The APS test may give false negative or false positive results, which may result in unnecessary medical intervention.
Which makes men who are already reluctant to get tested even more hesitant.
Pass the test or not?
We asked two experts for their opinion.
In the studies in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it's difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another European study found a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who had not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you have a 30 to 40 percent higher chance of metastasis if you don't get screened.
So I recommend testing at age 50, or at age 40 if you have a direct relative who has had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at greater risk.
The key is to make the right decision once you've been diagnosed with cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and there are lazy cancers.
We really need to make the patient understand the risk of their cancer, offering them the options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that don't affect their long-term life, and instead opting for active disease surveillance in those cases.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and life-threatening.
We're going to suggest that they be monitored and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
Increasingly, the criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are being set out in detail.
So I recommend you take the test anyway.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if you should have it or not.
