In addition, Mr Beaulieu stresses the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"Passing a screening test doesn't give you cancer".
The Higgs boson has been stripped clean
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
This boson is thought to be involved in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, that's all.
And then, it's the last particle that the Standard Model predicts exists -- our best, or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but that has yet to be observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's not yet completely certain that it's the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we're holding a genuine new particle, and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Let's just assume that it is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is a law in this world that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way you can break that rule - and don't try too hard, you'll get hurt.
But even though particle physics is a strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From this, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a nasty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure website of Berkeley Laboratories: mesons, which we won't discuss here, and "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson is thought to be somehow related.
These bosons, I must point out here, are not all as exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this column, it is because of an extraordinarily mundane boson: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When a charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "distorts" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "interference" arises an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and thus one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that it's another field, the Higgs field, that has to be "disrupted" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, kind of like a frozen pond that only a very large rock could scratch the surface of.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometer ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles, not all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't -- a piece of paper, for example, will never stick by itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, yours) don't.
Now, what can all this research "bring" to the table, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and the predictions of the MS.
Many are eager to find one, for the slightest difference could open the door to a "new physics" and fill in some holes in the Model.
It must be said that it still has huge flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (oops!).
But we haven't found any such discrepancies at CERN until now.
Effects
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr and Mrs All-World is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that it will not.
Here's the thing: In the early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work was going to spark.
They saw some scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we've already heard from the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - that the laser was originally seen as a "laboratory gadget".
Can you imagine?
And then, applications can also come from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle invented a small light sensor in 1969 while working on optics.
This sensor, though not at all his original intention, now serves as the "eye" for all the world's digital cameras, and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
That doesn't mean, of course, that the activities at the LHC are necessarily going to transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, you never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With its Commission dying with dignity, Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a draft law is being prepared.
But much remains to be done in this vital area.
Duty tried to look into it.
Only a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
He had been suffering from prostate cancer for two years.
"They had given me five years to live, I did seven", he said, half fig, half grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice, Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that", he says.
The disease is doing its job. It's a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone, even eating alone.
Sitting down to a delicious lunch, he resigned himself to being served.
He's brave, he can even smile, talk to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhea", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"We learn in our lives that a man urinates standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
For some people, going back to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept the regression, he says.
Because many palliative care practitioners feel that great moments are occurring at the very heart of this decline.
The patients who come to Victor-Gadbois hospice are all cancer patients.
They have a life expectancy of three months at most.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For 89-year-old A., the worst fear is that she will die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease has brought me to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life", she said, before agreeing to be put on a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son from Italy in the next few days.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide care and food.
It's palliative care, which is when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's not much when you know we're all gonna die.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Whether it be in terms of physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
The dying person will be offered brandy or Pepsi mouthwash, as required.
Diabetics will no longer have to control their blood sugar.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, it's his son who's gonna finish the beer at the dead man's feet.
"You help the family as much as you help the patient", says Nathalie Savard, a director of nursing.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, days follow one another but they are not alike.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying his last family gathering in the courtyard, resting on his pillows as a toast is poured out in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"In the last six months, there are still three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under 45", worries Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems in access to palliative care
It is said that 77 percent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care - care designed to ease the pain of a terminally ill patient, whether at home, in a hospital, or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this serious lack of health care in Quebec that has caused several palliative care doctors to fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by top officials in palliative care, including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not sufficiently efficient to ensure that everyone will have the right to quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
She says that recently I saw a patient spend 14 days in the ER in excruciating pain, with no relief.
I'm afraid patients are only asking to die because they're not getting proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists are working hard on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helen Richard's chances of survival were already slim when she stopped a grueling course of chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she said that she regretted that I stopped fighting.
But she told me I was finished!
Not Almighty Healing
Dr. Martel believes that 90 percent of patients who ask to die thank their caregivers for not granting their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, 8 percent of patients are unwilling to take pain medication.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is the practice of putting the patient to sleep until death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't hear that part of the pain anymore.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the option of having this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not cured always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanise me", it means "I want relief".
