With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is the opposite of current monetary exchanges, which are based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been recorded on the network's 15,000 computers.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to the global trade in real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is distinct from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to progress in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are both ledger keepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the same way as an e-mail.
Except a user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins actually exist in the public ledger, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write down this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will be privileged to add this extra line.
This is a phase of file hashing, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter, unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "chopping" the whole thing.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once the number is found, the other nodes can easily check that it is the correct one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to cheat, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided in half regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
So the number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but they're divisible by a hundred millionth, which leaves room...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase in computing power.
The network's life has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin were hacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The flaw is not in the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Powerful players like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80 percent of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, "giant payments" were made.
"Thirty thousand dollars was exchanged", says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real money) or contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which come back cheaper.
The wearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in the home of the merchant, who does not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is provide an address that a phone can "take a picture and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if the currency succeeds.
We left Afghanistan.
And then what?
French troops have withdrawn from their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the US are expected to follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take back its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, not expect anything from us.
It is mainly the Afghan peasants who we have punished as terrorists.
And us, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who are refugees in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the presence of foreign armies, as in the Soviet times.
They want to defend their traditions, ancient and archaic, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajik.
Tolerated, sometimes aided by local insurgents, they will no longer be as the West becomes more discreet.
The French troops' departure from Nijrab, which I watched from the top of the almond-tree hills with French loans, was orderly.
The convoys of trucks and armored vehicles reached Kabul unattacked, overflown by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was empty, the country burning and bloodshed due to fighting between different factions.
Their taking over the country was then seen as a sort of liberation, a return to security.
The Afghans paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants overtaken by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved in recent times.
Former mujahideen, Afghan government and current Taliban are joining forces in a desire to keep women in a lower position.
The main figures of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land to sell it for building land to refugees who had come back from Iran and Pakistan, getting huge U.S. outsourcing contracts.
They have become disrespectful of themselves; most of them have not fought themselves.
People, as I heard in the countryside, long for a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have benefited from the American bounty: the capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They've been exposed to the modern world in exile in Iran or Pakistan, and they've enjoyed the benefits.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years old; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, a fifth of the total population.
In the cities, the public schools are full of girls and boys.
We must provide jobs for these young people who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of some leaders.
Everyone, including armed opponents, is addicted to cell phones; television, with its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, is watched everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will command it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already concerned with re-establishing provincial militias, which will escape the central government.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some decentralisation, like Western nations, but the US wanted to turn it into a centralised state with strong presidential power, abolishing the post of prime minister that had existed since the 1964 constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially in the run-up to the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and even before that.
No industry has been restored, no dam is in working order, no major irrigation system is being repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruit and vegetables.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ravaged by thirty years of war, government control of infrastructure would have been necessary.
Rumor has it that Afghanistan has immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that the Westerners were only there to take it.
Without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, or transportation to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist site and remain the province's largest employers.
It will also be necessary someday for Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are heavily dependent on imports and exports, to return to normal relations.
The French fighting troops were completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aid: high school for girls and boys, French department at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to accomplish the impossible task of matching aid and offensive actions, a "civil-military actions" department of the Ministry of Defense (CIMIC), which was abolished in 2012, has carried out, and had a small French NGO carry out, many community-based works and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
These labour-intensive works helped to contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increased arable land.
What will we leave as a souvenir after spending two billion euros on the military?
A much smaller budget would help to improve local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often at altitudes of over 2,000 metres.
The embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
If they are to be free from the insurgency of foreign groups, as the farmers have told me they want, they should be given a small, well controlled civilian aid that directly affects them.
A Constitution in the grip of Egypt
This is another poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
As Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which provisionally gives it full powers, he has decided to play it cool.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago the head of state gave the Assembly two months to complete its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal problems.
This new initiative has only increased the division in the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample the law".
The supporters of the resolution claim that this is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short time that forced the Brethren to abandon their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems confident that Egyptians will vote in his favour, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
This is especially true since this use of a hasty vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I keep the full powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent assembly, overwhelmingly Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the declaration of the constitution, they had slammed the door, feeling they had not been able to make their views known.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles were voted on most of the time unanimously.
Some commentators have even laughed at the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, with some committee members feeling that the constituent's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, has 234 articles.
Despite all the attention, Article 2 remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", the liberals reply, seeing it as a mere communication trick.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, particularly in verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egyptologist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
It is the first sign of a theocracy".
The Liberal fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university will be far less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some of them trained in the French system", says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity about Article 220, because the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
It refers to fiqh in particular.
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on it".
The text voted yesterday is being heavily criticized for its religious aspect and for the extensive powers it gives the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are much smaller than they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights groups have demanded.
The Commission has also expressed its concern about the text, which it considers to be a liberty-killing measure.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly the press.
Moreover, no article is more about protecting women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive point, she said, was the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
The support of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land is a combination of the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comforts, and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has selected five main reasons for you to go to Israel.
Go worship in the holy places
They meet at the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptism wells" will be touched by divine grace.
Galilee is the land of Jesus' miracles - where he turned water into wine, where he walked on water, where he calmed a storm, and where he miraculously caught fish.
It was there that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But the place where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
The faithful walk the Street of Sorrows or the Way of the Cross (Latin: la Via Dolorosa).
The road starts near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to the Stone of Anointing and Burial.
Here is the Christian center of the world, the symbol of salvation for mankind.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is built on the spot where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest place for the Jews - the Western Wall, the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.E.
According to tradition, people of different religions leave small words and prayers on the altar that are then answered.
Travel in the High Country
Visit the ruins of the fortress of Massada, an ancient refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C.E. for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only climbers can go there on their own.
For others, a cable car takes them to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, at an altitude of between 1,600 and 2,040 m, is the ski resort of Mount Hermont, which is a popular winter destination for tourists.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs say that pagan gods once dwelt on the mountain's top.
Visiting the most unique museums
This country is home to almost 300 museums.
It's impossible to visit all of them in one trip.
Here are five of the most interesting ones that are really worth checking out.
First, the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the very old Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in caves in the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, you can visit the Hammam Al-Basha with its Turkish baths made up of castings of visitors and watchmen of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guidebooks or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are not accepted.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Memorial Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, which looks back on the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You walk in and you go into total darkness.
The stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major resorts in Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea, and the Dead Sea.
Each of these has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and giant aquariums.
Note: You can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, since the water temperature does not drop below 70 degrees Fahrenheit [21°C], while the air temperature can reach 90 degrees Fahrenheit [23°C].
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim in it all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world. It is the lowest point on Earth, at 1,300 feet [417 m] below sea level.
The blue water contains brine and is very easily trapped by bathing, even by those who cannot swim.
The landscapes around it are surreal in their beauty.
People come to the area to get treated with salt water, silt, and medicinal sludge, to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and simply to relax.
Unlock the Secrets of the Ancient World
They are kept by the ancient city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which links Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life right here.
Tourists especially enjoy strolling along narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
They say if you touch the walls of the street that match your sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take pictures from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theater, "conquering" the crusader fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the chief city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For travel, it is best to use dollars instead of euros, since they are easily exchanged for shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost like an underground funicular.
The fare for all public transport is 6 shekels and you can change for 1:30 hours.
In Israel, Jewish tradition requires that the Sabbath be observed on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transportation are closed.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales, and both milk and meat dishes.
There are a variety of dishes made from lamb and beef, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, various sauces, ground chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk around with a proud face.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These felines love to be out in the country and they don't mind being treated.
Renting a car varies by brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance is $15 a day.
Renting a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels a day.
The average entrance to the museum is 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
Most of these were travelers and vacationers from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, goes to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists debate the law on compulsory language testing, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the victims are from Central Asia - Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families back home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force that states that every migrant worker must pass a Russian language exam.
At present, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, in time, the Federal Migration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, Russian history and legal foundations will be validated.
You will need to validate your knowledge of Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian is the official language are exempt.
The law also does not apply to persons who obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
The initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders had already asked the question in the press many times: what will it do?
What will the requirement to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, the immigration officials say, it will reduce the number of people who suffer "from work slavery".
Many speak of defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the Russian Federal Migration Service office in Tajikistan.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organised selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems are for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future migrant is bound to encounter dishonest people who, under the guise of helping him, will provide him with a "trip" to a crowded house where he and dozens of his peers will be tormented for months without food and paper and must toil 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised something, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken away, and they do not get the expected salary", says Tolib Charipov, head of the Migration Services Directorate for Work of the Tajik Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to come to Russia to earn money say that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to visit but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajik can afford even a decent primary education.
Their families do not even have enough to feed their children, let alone clothe them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach their teens, they start earning money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and worthless".
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The exams will be for only legal immigrants.
Without a statute, there will be no examination or official work afterwards.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or not"
Many immigrants say that it is not so easy to obtain a legal status in Russia.
The reason is administrative barriers and still language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money - between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know we have fake papers, we have no registration, hence the extortion cases.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, to buy cigarettes, tea", said Uumed Khouchkadamov, a Tajik citizen.
"Hurry up, don't skimp and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art"
From the first day of the language law, it was discovered that the immigrant registration papers were not the only ones to be forged.
Several fake language examination certificates have already been confiscated by the employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The counterfeit papers are from a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners were not disappointed. Each migrant who hoped to make the exams easier had to pay seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Officials and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "pieces of paper".
The authorities may give migrant workers who failed to pass the exam at the first attempt time to take language courses.
Moreover, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs in fields that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior is not in charge of the arms market.
The proportion of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of Internal Affairs is proposing tougher laws against civilian weapons.
This is how authorities have reacted to recent incidents, from the shooting at weddings to the murder of seven people by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
Police want to ban the carrying of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age to obtain a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the State Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "screwing up".
An open letter has appeared on the Internet in which its authors, representatives of various firing centers, demand that "this senseless hardening" be abandoned.
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime expert for the BBC, told the Russian Service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Interior, in a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a registered firearm in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tightening the laws on civilian weapons will not stop criminals from sourcing their weapons on the black market.
They say that today in Moscow you can buy any weapon at a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims to control the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: From the factory to the officer
The black market for weapons is provided through several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Headquarters.
Screenshot from a website that takes orders for weapons
The first is the "military trail", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians", Baranets explains.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stores and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
The illegal guns are going on sale from the military warehouses.
Many of these have been hit by explosions.
"Some of the fires were deliberately set to cover up the shortfall", says the former soldier.
Baranets thinks the weapons manufacturers are behind it.
"There are private arms factories that are not competing on the international market and sell the weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow", says one expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A large proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has formed and organises the supply", adds the former soldier.
Where did the guns come from?
The experts estimated the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, say researchers, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market ended up there "because of the lack of employees whose work is related to weapons", the report says.
According to the researchers, 17 percent of the weapons come from military conflict sites, 14 percent are stolen during manufacture, and 5 percent come from "clandestine searches".
A salesman and consultant at a gun shop who asked not to be named said that for a long time no one had bought the weapons found by the clandestine excavation specialists; they were too old.
Most often, he says, the sellers go to the military warehouses to pick up the new goods.
The person buys a unit, for example a TT pistol, through a sign.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a barrier.
"He takes it into town and sells it for £900 a unit with two chargers", he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a control purchase from illegal arms dealers", adds the seller.
