We started to get interested in questions of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Only half a century ago, we were experimenting on plants.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from the varieties on Earth.
Then we put insects into orbit, small breeding Drosophila flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to study how an embryo develops in weightlessness.
You get a perfectly normal chick out of it.
That's when the problems start.
"The problem is that the chick needs to find support, get on its feet and start moving", explains Vladimir Sychev, director of the laboratory at the Institute of Biomedical Problems at the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP).
The chicks were unable to find any support and were moving about in a disorderly fashion.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely paralyzed.
The chicks didn't respond to light or sound.
Sadly, they would simply die after four days.
"We took their eyes out twice and then we gave up because it's just impossible to work with them there", explains Vladimir Sychev after seeing the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, the Bion biosatellite will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, we haven't discovered anything supernatural.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment.
