The head of the SFI (Supreme Audit Institution for Public Finance) said: "The control of pseudo-self-employment (in Czech "Švarc system") has failed because of politicians.
The Czech Republic has competent public procurement inspectors and quality legislation but lagged behind in its enforcement.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, the vice-president of the Supreme Authority for Public Finance Control in an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and in my opinion that is what is missing from us", Kala said in his comment on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice the approach of Petr Nečas' "Švarc system".
The Prime Minister recently said that the SDGs would not burden contractors with controls; is that allowed or forbidden?
"The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot stop an authority that is supposed to go and inspect to enforce the law", Kala says.
At the meeting of the Committee on Audit in the Chamber of Deputies you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of the two countries were compared.
What was the specific question?
This is a parallel monitoring which we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for the way in which public procurement is managed and specific national legislation and practice follow it.
We have put all this together and although this control procedure is not yet complete, we have found some very interesting differences: generally speaking, our legislation may be 'harder and of better quality', but according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to constantly develop more detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote ourselves to the application of the law itself.
How can this project help you in practice and what does it mean for you?
This is the kind of common control which should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), so as to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering the market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this.
It may be that the system is so overwhelmed with paperwork that those looking for flaws will find far more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems in the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SCI or a different way of organising it?
As regards the institutions, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is similarly organised and has a slightly different board, functions there, but the two institutions operate in a basically similar way.
The powers are also somewhat similar, with one nuance in relation to our system: Germany being a federal structure, it therefore also has such accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The BRH can only control federal money, which is the state's resources here.
The public funds managed by the regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the Länder's accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, but in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model but it is certainly not possible to say that it is doing better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, I'm sure not, but I repeat, I have no comparison data.
But it must also be said that this country which we regard as a model also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has the amendment to the Public Procurement Act meant for you as an institution, and are its effects already being felt?
This amendment has been introduced relatively recently and has not yet had any impact on our control operations.
Since we do a posteriori checks, we must expect a certain delay.
Our observations are only for the moment about the process of preparing future controls - we have launched a new 'risk of mismanagement' tool with which we have screened almost 14 000 public contracts - these changes will of course be felt there, because the thresholds have been changed and the conditions of certain types of tendering procedures and so on.
Do you consider the adoption of this law as a benefit or as an additional burden on the administration?
I think this legislation is a step in the right direction and I hope the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and impossible to follow.
Under the previous regulation, the provider (e.g. the regional council in the case of regional operational programmes) already obliged the subjects to accept that any breach of the market law would mean a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it really useful to make the law more stringent in this way?
No, not like this, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or abuse the system but not punish those who make formal mistakes without consequences on the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the solution?
Let's see where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDG would not bother contractors with checks on the so-called Švarc system - what does that mean?
Is the Švarc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be enforced in some way, so if it prohibits something, even the head of government cannot prevent an authority from going in to inspect and enforce the law.
He can say, "We're going to change the law and allow it", but he can't say we're going to act like nothing happened.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formalities to be completed, precisely to protect the tender.
But it is also tragic that a bidder is eliminated solely because of formal defects.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied justly and that is what I think is lacking in us.
