Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the European Space Agency's ministers, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the agency, the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and over the years has participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's journey into space, however, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, enthusiastic Poles were working on space flights; they were not always understood.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas from his ground-breaking work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left cold listeners and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a major promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned proponent of astronautics, and his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925 a rocket-powered drainage system was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, we do not know the author or the details of this project.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was intended to propel or brake the drystein.
The only information known about this draisine is from the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The surviving documents show that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937 the plans for a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialist press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects to use rocket technology were conducted by the temporary scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee was formed in 1937, but after two years of operation, the outbreak of war interrupted its activities.
After the war, further works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of a company was in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problème, which contained four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to the study of space
At that time, projects for artificial satellites had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held the position until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This rocket, with a range of 1,800 meters, was 80 centimeters long and weighed just under 5 kilograms.
An improved version, the RM-1A, was subsequently built and, during the summer of 1959, flight tests of the RM-2 two-stage rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kilograms.
The next prototype should have been capable of carrying out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But by 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B it was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 23 miles.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed at the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and in 1978 pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut in this programme.
