In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for decades.
The situation offered no positive outcome for the American administration, which could not abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
This was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was further aggravated later by the failure of the attempt to release the hostages by force.
The diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, depicts an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After some complicated adventures, they met at the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
Working with Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran under a daunting cover: they left the country on Canadian passports as members of a film crew to do background checks for a big-screen science fiction film.
Combination of the sexes
Exfiltration expert Tony Mendez's plan requires the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on the film project, press conferences were held, and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film being based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is partly a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The scenes follow one another: documentary-style footage from Tehran (subtitled footage shows iconic photographs from the time of the events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed into the film, there are no major differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then there were scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a derided actor, he became a respected director, and his acting stopped provoking sarcastic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film after the dark detective Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The Town (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to be set in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his early films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the opening sequence of the embassy fall is impressive for its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake crew shooting in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to be content with a subject that actually had few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the word.
He does very well, sometimes he adds some elements to reality and here the result is not always so elegant (the scene where the threat of a crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the chase on the runway is pretty close).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipative nature, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their roles as Hollywood co-stars, their characters would have deserved a bigger role and they are far from alone in this.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, but is seen with moderate interest, appreciating the direction and retro style of the 1970s.
He's got the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in some ways, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the trick.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circuses
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public survey on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch a competition for the most absurd regulations or ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is considering adopting a quota of 40 per cent women for the management of large European companies recently was the reason for our decision", said the organiser of the survey, Patrik Nacher, to the newspaper Právo.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
Until now, however, women have had an advantage in terms of life insurance rates because they are objectively less of a risk to insurance companies.
People can report any other equally amazing idea of the 'EU workshop' until the end of the year.
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the obligation to add organic components to fuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to higher egg prices.
Criticism has also been expressed in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term 'spit butter' or the withdrawal from sale of conventional ampoules.
Good bananas should be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often responds under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (the Czech Republic currently imposes its banks' demands by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of lobbyists are also behind, for example, the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an 'abnormal curve'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonizing non-homogeneous national standards which complicated trade.
Standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some states, who claim that existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize may be awarded in this investigation to the EU regulation of last year that inflatable balloons must bear a warning that children under 8 years of age must not inflate without adult supervision.
The EU referred to a US survey that showed that balloons are the leading cause of children's deaths from choking among toys.
A similar restriction applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing fair trumpets.
We have some weird ideas here, too.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this topic for Greece, anyone with an official position within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, the server Bankovnípoplatky.com named in this survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the volume limits for canned mushrooms and was thus subject to a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found the idea of paying money to some countries because they have no access to the sea and the idea of granting a grant to apply for grants interesting.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"The fact that we don't have the sea makes us disabled.
We will ask the European Union for a refund". This was the view expressed in the autumn of 2004 by the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
He argued that, because of our wheat production and the so-called interventionist purchases, the State had full stocks and had to export them.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to the Czech request and organised a tender for the purchase of wheat from countries without access to the sea.
The grant grants were offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), and were to be used to draft applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says that "weird regulations are rare".
While regulations are often criticised in the Member States, many experts say that the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the Union's functioning and its overall development are to be commended.
More serious, for example, according to experts, is the problem of the use of EU grants for projects which have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration but which have been imposed by Member States during budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, is fighting in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a fight in which it does not always win) is very emotional for the Czechs.
If after six years of fighting the Germans and the Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name 'Olomoucké tvarůžky', our producers had to replace the name 'Tuzemský rum' which dates back to the 19th century with the name 'Tuzemák'.
Only products made from cane sugar alcohol, and not from beet sugar, may be called rum.
The official EU list of registered products now includes world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck breadcrumbs or Parma ham, Karlovy Vary biscuits ("Karlovarské suchary"), Pohořelice and Třeboň carp ("Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr") and Žatecký hop ("Žatecký chmel").
The Pardubice spice bread ("Pardubický perník") and the cakes called "Horices" ("hořické trubičky") can also be proud of their Community brand.
People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur, says Senator Okamura
Senator, what's the idea of running for president?
It's not about being a senator or president that matters to me.
If everything worked smoothly in our country, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can't stand to see the country being looted for the last 20 years, the thieves not in jail and taxes and the retirement age going up.
I had no ambition to become a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, then I try to make a solution to change it.
And since I am over forty and an independent, non-party member, I have no other choice but to run for president or for the Senate.
You entered the Senate but quickly made your way to the Castle.
Isn't that how you turn your back on those who elected you?
I've always said I'd fight for the castle based on the Senate election results.
I later made it clear that if I was elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not the function, it's just a tool to help me realize my vision.
That's why I need the greatest influence and the widest mandate.
The problem is not just that as a nation we're clamouring at the bar or in front of our TV sets, but that we're trampling on those who are trying to bring about change.
Add to this the media's defamatory reporting and confusing freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, it has been alleged that I bribed journalists or that I was an adviser to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's get to your visions.
You have started the fight for the castle with the themes of political and criminal liability and retroactive tax returns of more than twenty million [CZK] as your battleground.
You must change the law to that end.
As president, you do not have that power and only the full Senate can propose legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
When I as a citizen pushed for tourist guiding to be a liberal profession, I won.
The problem is the political stuff: when someone comes from the left or the right with a good project, it is deliberately rejected and it delays the citizens.
As an independent, member of no party, I have a much better chance of getting the support of all the parliamentary parties.
I have the advantage of being able, without categorization and dogma, to take from each party what is best for our country and apply it.
Do you consider yourself more of a right-wing or left-wing man?
From a Czech point of view, I feel like people put me on the left.
For me, whether it's a little left or right, it doesn't really matter.
For me, the important thing is that we move forward.
What matters to me is not whether people are on the left or the right, but to bring people together.
I always support any solution that contributes to the common good, even if it is proposed by the Communist Party or the ODS and I act equally impartially against bad ideas.
Do you get angry when someone calls you a populist?
But what you said proves that.
When you make a business plan in a company, you also have some optimal goal and vision.
You're trying to get close to it.
Some may call it populism, but all the proposals I'm talking about have been implemented by the world and talked about by renowned experts.
But without the support of Parliament, you're left with slogans.
You won't survive long in politics with that.
Do you think that if you go out and talk to people, you will be successful, for example, in imposing property and criminal liability?
I don't have any other choice.
I have to convince the politicians, the journalists and the public and try to rally them to my side to impose it.
If I were elected President, I would have no problem broadcasting live on television my request to the presidents of the parliamentary parties to legislate on the material and criminal liability of politicians, civil servants, judges and prosecutors.
They should then perhaps explain why they do not want it.
When there is a strong personality who identifies abuse, it will be possible to put pressure on the political scene.
Take for example the election of the president by direct vote, which was achieved thanks to public pressure.
I confess, without ambiguity, to be an amateur, not a genius or an intellectual.
I try to find allies for my opinions and my visions.
I have just entered politics and I am trying to get the majority support for my programme.
I'm trying to get things done on my own, and if it doesn't work, I'll quit in six years and go back to the private sector.
It's like Okamura is supposed to save the Czech Republic.
I'm not a savior.
I know that one person alone cannot make a difference, which is why I went to a number of people and asked them to stand for the Senate elections.
I met Radim Jančura, but he refused because of the amount of work.
At least I supported the investigative journalist Jana Lorencová who exposed the oil fraud.
I ran because people are really upset, but now I'm hesitant.
Sixty percent of the people did not vote and those who did, for the most part, gave their vote to a representative of the establishment.
There are only two independents in the Senate.
The people have elected a Senate that will be unlikely to force change.
Nevertheless, I will fight for my vision, for example the direct election of mayors and regional prefects.
Are you thinking of starting your own party ?
No, not yet, because I don't have time to check the history of every potential member for stainless steel and I don't have the financial means to do so.
I also don't have any money for my presidential campaign, I only have 20 grand in my "transparent" account.
You don't have any money?
Speaking of tax returns, what's yours?
I estimate my personal property to be worth about $60 million.
I have a plot of land in Prague worth 25 million, an apartment worth 10 million, another apartment worth 8 million, a collection of artwork worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Škoda Superb worth 1 million and a few million on my account.
By the way, I own an Aston Martin, because it was a childhood dream: I always loved James Bond, who drove cars, was gay with women and fought evil and abuse.
You drive an Aston Martin, you have a fortune worth $60 million and you don't have any campaign money?
You want to change the Republic but you don 't want to invest your own money ?
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million dollars for this campaign.
Should I go into debt?
I've already put two and a half million into the campaign.
The fact that I have no sponsors shows that my programme is not attracting much interest.
I don't have to pay for this campaign out of my own pocket.
My campaign expenses are largely covered by the salary I will receive as a senator.
But I couldn't live on it, for example, paying for my son's English school which costs 30 grand a month.
If my only goal was to make money, I would not run for office.
So you're going to continue your business activities to make a living?
Didn't you say you were going to silence your activities?
But this is not related to the amount of this remuneration.
As I promised, I've partially reduced my activities.
For example, my assistant will be running the travel agency in the spring.
People would like me to be a good Samaritan to save the Republic.
I must have something to live on.
What was your usual monthly salary when you were a contractor?
I was making and I'm still making between two hundred and four hundred thousand.
If I were president, I'd stop my business activities.
You can find this interview in the Saturday edition of the newspaper Práva.
The architects at MVRDV prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination.
"I think it's funny, it looks very futuristic, it's something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, says: "Yes, this building is indeed beautiful".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everybody has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to one of those dingy libraries anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town with nothing attractive on the outskirts of Rotterdam, has a rather unusual record.
The municipality of 80,000 has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To restore some of the brain's neurons, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture by reproducing the seven fictional bridges on the euro notes in the form of pretty little miniatures of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive was limited.
The city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of the statistics - to build a library!
Winy Maas, of the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold stick drawings and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the judges were still looking at each other, bewildered and shrugging, Maas, brazenly, piled his favorite books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech backed by activist arguments with one: "Dear Common!"
Here is my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the $30 million mountain has risen from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few townhouses and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project was also selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dreary little town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of astonishing ugliness, with white façades that suggest a dairy farm, has become a modern architectural masterpiece.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to Reading
First printing: Eldorado from the book under the cheese bell.
Although an elevator takes you to the heart of the mountain, the real joys of reading and architecture are revealed when you step on the floor of the building and discover its topography.
The interior, made entirely of glass, is bright and clear, the floor made of Dutch brick and the elegant streetlights speak unmistakably the language of the city's public squares.
The city atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And books everywhere, books and books.
"Normally, the library shelves are along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal", explains Willy Maas.
We completely upended the traditional spatial configuration and opened up the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been cleverly laid out: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental centre and the technical centre of the building.
A special beauty lies in the black rails of the library, which are sometimes panels, sometimes balustrades, sometimes ramps of stairs.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of hardened buildings don't want unfamiliar materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
So one day we found an ad hoc agricultural waste in a Friesian farmhouse.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane of one millimeter thickness has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves us time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time, in such quantities into four-centimeter-thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, Landbouwplastic (KPL) changes colour to a dark, homogeneous and durable material, which smells like a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the mountain's summit.
Nearly 500 meters up, the literary café offers a spectacular view of the city, as well as Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
These create an atmosphere, but they are most important in maintaining the ideal humidity level of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's amazing, but with all the glass, this building is a model ecological project", says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun shines only briefly inside, even on good days.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass façade serve as a sunshade, blocking much of the sun's rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds will take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic computer scientist mentioned earlier, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his or her personal library.
This helped to fill the gaps in the library, which was not yet fully filled - it now has 70,000 books.
The concept is a success.
The rays are pouring in everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library".
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration".
This is how MVRDV has achieved the core discipline known in professional jargon as 'identity building'.
Spijkenisse has written a new page in literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
It is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role".
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, the decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be careful, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have any difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy defined by the Americans and to introduce a German foreign policy.
The lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans were thus facing several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still groping for that role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What does the term 'normal' foreign policy mean for Germans?
It shows a willingness to take positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, and therefore by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China and the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany are to some extent different from those of the other great powers.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany has important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
I would not, however, attach too much importance to this, because it is not a purely one-sided relationship.
But this is at any rate a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by abstaining in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and Americans understand the German position perfectly.
I therefore believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus shown that it must be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are differing views on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and most European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic American political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political situation in the country, the government cannot of course defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from over enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Does Germany have any difficulty in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States with the position of its major European partners?
I don't think that makes it any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today this is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must assert their unique position.
That is what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that Germany will play a driving role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of its relations with Israel.
This has always been a delicate question.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role which will make them more independent.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international scene, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have trouble taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still uncomfortable with it and, for obvious reasons, the country is still having difficulty playing a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany decides to weigh more, there are many anti-German sentiments.
It doesn't make it any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with neighbors and with very different opinions, and that is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is only decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling the void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and they're just less appreciated, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are brands known around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a registered trademark in China, but it has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the company bearing the trade mark cannot bring a complaint.
And even if she could, it's not certain she'd win.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a firm specializing in infringement of Far Eastern property rights.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
The copycats only need a few more letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we're going to register Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we're going to register Prada-Kny.
German companies are also being legally copied, such as sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a file containing the registrations made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma brand, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become world champions in copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell almost all counterfeit goods.
However, Pattloch's case is different: his clients instruct him to address the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It's a term used to describe women who marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this", Pattloch says.
"The brand is diluted, the uniqueness is lost, the reputational damage is enormous".
The financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially for the expensive flagship products.
According to data from market research firm CLSA, China is the world's third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market with an annual volume of EUR 15 billion.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the register of trade marks and such procedures are expensive.
The latter can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch mentions the trials in which the court rejected the complaint because after a long time the name under criticism had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is unlucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist, as he would have damaged his brand in China.
In this area, sometimes the law of the jungle prevails.
Famous cases also involve graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo buyer, had previously used a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost to plagiarists in Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the eye of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing, however, admits that it had some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the Office is said to have gone from a "working emergency to a normal situation" last year.
The number of unresolved opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were reportedly closed, a 75% increase from the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 procedures remain pending at the office.
The cost of action
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trade mark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the agency, this is a record and it means that China is for the tenth time in a row at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office reportedly recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each recording earned an average of 1,280 yuan, or $160.
A legal battle costs far more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For over seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
It is true that the Germans have been able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"It is our fault, because surnames cannot be protected in Germany", explains Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The Office of the Trade Mark Office therefore rejected the objection of the Municipalities.
Freudenberg won the next two cases, but the other side continues to fight to this day.
The Need for Vigilance
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and praises the professionalism of the judges.
However, he adds: "The process is long, exhausting, and costs us a lot of time and money".
The internal costs are also difficult to assess, and the Archives Department has even had to review records from the last 100 years to provide evidence.
