Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common STIs include HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pubes and scabies are parasitic STIs.
Which groups are most affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are common in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five reported cases of syphilis in Germany are caused by male-to-male sexual contact.
In heterosexual adults, infections associated with chlamydia, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), blennorrhea and the human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The HIV transmission rate among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, but about 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
The rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher among young people than among other groups of the population.
According to European statistics, three quarters of all infections are among young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, the human papilloma virus is common among young people in Germany.
What is the trend in the number of infections?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases need to be reported.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years, from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been declining.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared with the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, and the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they do not usually cause pain or other symptoms and are therefore hidden.
How can we protect ourselves?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they don't protect 100 percent.
This is because the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close bodily contact.
Experts therefore recommend that anyone who frequently changes sex partners have regular checkups.
Most STIs that are detected early can be cured and delayed effects can be prevented.
