The hardest job in the world: human mules from Kawah Ijen
For four euros, volcano carriers in Indonesia risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilograms of sulfur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
He has to work daily to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gas from the earth's interior solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large stones of sulfur, weighing a total of about 70 kilograms, he places them in two bamboo baskets and carries them over steep paths on his shoulders.
It is only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters above sea level, but the weary porters climb this distance at a tortoise-like pace for more than 40 minutes, keeping their balance and measuring their steps so as not to trip and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell to her death from the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners in Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract.
Once on top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and with the pains of carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the two miles to the scale that a mining company has installed just below at 6,000 feet [1,850 m].
The company, PT Candi Ngrimbi, has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, in effect, its employees, who are paid 662 Indonesian rupees (US$5.00) per kilo of sulfur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since the mineral is a staple in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"We make about 46,000 rupees ($3,500) a trip because we carry about 70 kilograms", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes three hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees ($14,500) at the end of the day.
Although it may seem like a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees ($1.40) a day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees ($1.40)", says the porter who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the work was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, a constant cough, and irritated eyes from the toxic gas.
At 27, he has spent three years of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulfur has already started to cost him money despite covering his face with a mask and wearing special gloves.
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and irritated eyes from the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
