The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter he admits not to know 20 of the people on his friend list.
"I'm not worried about it because we have something in common, like music", he says.
The boy said that no one had ever made a pass at him or asked for his address or phone number.
"If they pressured me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account", he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences now known as cyberbullying are not unfamiliar to the young boy.
A friend of mine's family was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he says.
Victim, according to José, didn't close his account.
"He only passed it on as a private profile".
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a secure manner.
Unlike Jorge, this youngster would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if I was angry or upset.
"Even though I know it's cyberbullying", he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in Education and Learning, believes that the goal of social media is to inform children and adolescents.
"The Internet started as a way to find information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are those children and young people who are born with technology.
"We, the digital immigrants, are the ones who have to teach them, while we are learning", she says.
He adds that the subject is complex, "because we are asking them to have a clear standard of what to disclose, publish or say at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what they care about most is being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences", she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and teens about privacy is to use questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it is no use", she says.
Then Porras lists some examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to post a picture of you like a friend's picture you posted?
Do you know what other people are posting about you?
When you identify party photos, do you ask other people's permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you're doing at all times?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, everyone should act with respect, morality and other principles, it should be the same on social networks", she says.
The Commission shall be assisted by the European Parliament.
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher, and educational consultant, says that it is vital that parents carefully read the terms and conditions of social networking sites.
By understanding each of these terms, parents will have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an Internet account.
"For example, age and what is allowed to share or post", he says.
Guardia says it is vital to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public.
The 6th Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was announced earlier and theoretically adopted by the 7 delegates present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit closed, then claimed that it would be published at any time on the Peruvian government website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents were exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among journalists was provided by the press officers of some of the UNASUR governments attending the meeting, except for the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit's "final statement", but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American-Arab Summit (SASA) and, on that occasion, despite press demands, it did not release the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited information gathering as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with Chile and Peru agreeing jointly to accept a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice which sets a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear arguments from both sides in Lima's trial of Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and implement the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today", President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts", added President Piñera, shaking hands with President Humala, beside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it agreed to submit to the decisions of this international court, following a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the ouster of former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was instructed to open the morning deliberations and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total investment of USD 17 million.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He said that measures would be taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, 'economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and foreshadow a better future for our people,' concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve connectivity in South America, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a speech.
He mentioned that five of these projects were for Peru and were on the cross-sectional axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were for a larger connection with Ecuador although he did not give the most detailed details.
The final document also mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow it to re-enter the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, with integrated and good relations with its neighbours, was another theme discussed at the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico City on Saturday to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I will have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", said President Santos.
"We will review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will require a discussion with that country", he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday where they plan to witness the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, the Summit will see the bloc's defence ministers meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the presidency pro tempore of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship", says Rafael Correa.
President of Ecuador Rafael Correa today said that the creation of a common citizenship was an objective for which "South America, in this case, should follow the example of Europe".
President Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state television TV Peru that Europeans "killed each other in World War II" and other conflicts, "but now they are almost a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the project to establish a South American citizenship encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
"We must achieve free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case for the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make part of the past", he warned.
The Ecuadorian President also expressed his support for the re-establishment of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon States and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who are listening to us never compromise, but we South Americans have all signed it.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington with US funding", he said, referring to Ecuador's political asylum for WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa said he did not regret his decision, as he did not betray his principles, but instead respected his "deep democratic values and human rights".
It concluded that at the time, "there were reasonable suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected".
He also criticised the Swedish courts for requiring him to be questioned on his territory about an alleged sexual offence, even though "Sweden's own legislation allows for this to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian Embassy in London".
Correa claimed that there was a risk that Assange's mental and physical health would deteriorate.
"I have not spoken to him since he is in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, but nothing serious", the Ecuadorian president said.
His physical and mental health may deteriorate if he is confined to a small space and is unable to exercise outdoors.
"It affects everyone's health", he concludes.
Correa points out that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the granting of a safe pass to allow him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and European judicial authorities and he points out that he has had discussions in London to find a solution to the imprisonment of the WikiLeaks founder.
We do not negotiate with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a series of proceedings before different European bodies", he said.
And he thinks that "if Britain granted safe passage tomorrow, this would be over".
And if Sweden, as is fully permitted by its legislation, and as it has done in other cases, were to question Mr Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or by Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa used the occasion to reassert himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was "mediocrity, bad faith and lies that harm freedom of expression".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not malicious or perverse politicians but bad journalists who are hired by greed, blackmail and extortion", he said.
In this regard, he welcomed that it was not such journalists "nor the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador" and, rather than pushing for his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to continue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto over Paraguay in Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality, "this is destroying the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the Ecuadorian President considered as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not being respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We have to solve them as a whole to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence that the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile would be resolved in the same court and said that it was "beneficial for Latin America to take international action if both countries agree to accept a firm judgment".
Referring to the possibility of running for a third consecutive term in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, he said he saw the possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa has said that if he loses the February 2013 primary, he will retire from public life.
On a personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as those in Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be solved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this eventual victory but we must accept that responsibility", he said.
If I win, it will be my last presidential term and then I will retire from politics.
If we ever lose, I will too.
"It's my decision", he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that a routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse in President Chávez's health", he commented.
The Ecuadorian President took part today in the VI Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, which ended with a call for greater regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths are now caused by late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when the test result was confirmed - HIV positive.
"It's as if the sky had fallen on my head", he said, referring to the moment of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his own illness and started to learn about it and his determination was so strong that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), where he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
So even the director of one IMSS clinic refused to say goodbye to him "because he was speechless".
In those days, having AIDS was a death sentence.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, many people still arrive unaware of their illness when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and become victims of opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the AIDS outbreak began worldwide, at least after the first cases were reported, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG HIV Unit, citing the fact that this information was validated in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious diseases expert Andrade Villanueva said that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of damage to the immune system of patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs: up to 30 years for those with a CD4 count of 200 and up to 50 years for those with a CD4 count of 500.
Simply put, this means that for someone diagnosed HIV-positive at age 25, "as long as it is under control, he can live safely until age 75", explained the scientist interviewed.
To put this progress in context, the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While the death rate has fallen significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths has risen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to UNAIDS' annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients counted in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there have been 187 deaths up to May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral medicines has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we've never run out of drugs, but the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact: "Nine out of ten patients arrive with an opportunistic infection, and what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is earlier diagnosis and to do this, mass screening testing must be provided to all who ask for it".
The experts and members of the Jalisco State Council for AIDS Prevention (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to have his test done in a private laboratory simply because a friend had done it and who, despite his young age, was already HIV-positive and had Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you find out you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, I'd rather have fun three times a week", they say, but I'm not.
The change has been good, I eat right, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I am also responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, through his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
Let them get tested, if they've taken risks, the sooner they know if they're HIV positive, the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that they can live like everyone else, be responsible.
His message sums up the slogan of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the average citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the greatest of these lies in prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packs of a hundred, that's very good, but the result is that even today, some people still don't have access to condoms", he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
The question, "What are you going to do with it?" asked sarcastically and with judgment by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists, and health professionals is one that teenagers do not want to hear, says the reporter.
He proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters but be found in public toilet machines and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about promoting promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González said when asked if there would be a condom distribution in his administration.
"That's not how sex works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active", he said.
The numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state is the 4th state in the country in number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in number of HIV patients.
Ninety-two percent of infections are sexually transmitted, six percent are blood-borne, and two percent are perinatal.
An estimated 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for every recorded case, there are four or five people who don't know it.
A judgment upheld on appeal by a US court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a bad precedent for all national companies with branches in the neighbouring country and solvency problems.
It seems that the survival procedures of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the star-studded country, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the June 15 ruling by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of an embargo on their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court on three grounds.
First, while the trial judge points out that creditors must register under the U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, states that the main proceedings are in the form of commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases involving companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for Uniformity in International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, with the American Law Institute as the arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the intercompany vote, which was recognised as a critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican law recognizes this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the subsidiaries' votes remained, in any case the Vitro creditors who fought against this in the US courts, i.e. vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A fact omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation it had been facing since 2008 without stopping at the severe economic crisis facing the United States, which was passing costs on to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family company will appeal to the same court of appeal to have the vote taken in its entirety, that is, with the five judges, since only three had voted.
The insurance claim will claim non-prosperity and require a review of the case by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
More seriously, the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") detailing Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, stating that this exempted it from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it on par with Section 15 of the US Bankruptcy Act.
It also notes that the country has complied with the United Nations Commission on International Trade principles, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-part carambolage: they stun Vitro and they stun the country.
The general balance sheet
Complaints from the Mexican Aviation Association's unions against the company's former boss, Gastón Azcárraga Andrade, were ignored for several months, he was accused of fraudulent administration, the Airline Pilots' Association has already run into problems.
The court, headed by Carlos Díaz Chávez Morineau, has just filed a criminal complaint against the National Banking and Securities Commission, which is accused of obstruction of justice.
According to him, the inspection authority had consistently denied having provided information to the Attorney General of the Republic on an operation carried out by the contractor to withdraw 198 million pesos from the F/589 trust fund of IXE Bank on behalf of Mexicana de Aviación.
The funds were allegedly used to purchase shares in the Hotel Professional Administration.
As everyone knows, Azcárraga Andrade is the main shareholder of the Posadas hotel chain.
