Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
Basketball globe-trotter "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life connected to the court and, thanks to it, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as much knowledge of the local basketball history as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for over 60 years, whether as a minor league player, a player for the national basketball team, a manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the Basketball Federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation in the 90s", Reyes recalls during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life".
Reyes is not exaggerating when he makes that claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia that recall his extraordinary journey, are proof of this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, his most cherished are those of his time as a player with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a team co-manager or manager.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I was lucky enough to play in eight Vaqueros championships starting in 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or executive.
It was a lot of satisfying years, including five championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over the team", says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was the manager here at the University of Alabama at Birmingham, said to me, "I have a big player for you, six feet tall.
You want it?"
That's how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was a top marksman.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse was gonna help us try to win another.
He was happy to win the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At the time, he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's duties on the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the Pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth and should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian referee hadn't had us play the last game again, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and beat the U.S. team, which was pretty similar to the team that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the 1990 World Cup due to a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but they gave us a gold medal and a lot of joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Mar del Plata Pan American Games, we won gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
There's no doubt about it, this is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics at the international tournament level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Piculín.
And that's without taking into account his track record in the different leagues he's played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team made up of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I really like the work Leo Arill does with the young people.
What do you think is your greatest achievement in the federation?
Being part of the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What else is there to do?
There are things I would have liked to have done, such as regionalisation of minor categories.
For example, the boys from Ponce play only in their area and only face teams from other parts of the island in the national play-offs.
Today's youths travel and play too much when it's not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for executives, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
I usually listen to music, watch old videos on YouTube, enjoy time with my grandchildren, and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a ruthless, feared, manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for "Dallas" production company Warner Bros.
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the ironic role he loved most", the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas for this Thanksgiving holiday.
